ce:section.ce:para:
The N-GQDs/Fe3+ system was used as “turn on” sensor for AA detection. The mechanism is related with the redox reaction between Fe3+ and AA. AA reduces Fe3+ to Fe2+ and no electron transfer occurs from N-GQDs to Fe2+ then the fluorescence intensity of N-GQDs can be recovered. According to the results of PL recovering of N-GQDs/Fe3+, AA can be detected sensitively and selectively (Fig. 7
                     a). The PL intensity of N-GQDs is gradually recovered after the addition of AA; the calculation of LOD was carried out from the linear fitting of the PL intensity of N-GQDs/Fe3+ against the AA concentration (1–1000 μM; inset of Fig. 7a). However, a better correlation coefficient (0.991) was obtained in the concentration, range from 1 to 600 μM. The linear relationship is described as follows F–F0 = 0.649[C] – 13.07, where F and F0 stand for the PL intensity in the presence and absence of AA respectively, [C] is the AA concentration. The PL intensity reaches a maximum (66.6%) at 800 μM of AA. The LOD was 30.96 nM (with n = 5) and agree with previous reports of fluorescence sensors [7,29,32] Also, this value agree with other AA detectors based on colorimetry, electrochemistry, and chemiluminescence (Table 1
                     ) [11,70–75]. The determination of AA by fluorescence offers rapid and facile way compared to other methods. This result shows the use N-GQDs/Fe3+ as turn on detector for AA and the “on–off–on” photoluminescence mechanism for the N-GQDs is highly specific for the Fe3+ ions and AA.
